<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Scots_language&action=edit&section=14.php.html" title="Edit section: Consonants">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Consonants">Consonants</span></h3>
<table class="wikitable">
<tr>
<th>&#160;</th>
<th><a href="Bilabial_consonant" title="Bilabial consonant">Bilabial</a></th>
<th><a href="Labiodental_consonant" title="Labiodental consonant">Labio-<br />
dental</a></th>
<th><a href="Interdental_consonant" title="Interdental consonant">Dental</a></th>
<th><a href="Alveolar_consonant" title="Alveolar consonant">Alveolar</a></th>
<th><a href="Postalveolar_consonant" title="Postalveolar consonant">Post-<br />
alveolar</a></th>
<th><a href="Palatal_consonant" title="Palatal consonant">Palatal</a></th>
<th><a href="Velar_consonant" title="Velar consonant">Velar</a></th>
<th><a href="Labial-velar_consonant" title="Labial-velar consonant" class="mw-redirect">Labial-<br />
velar</a></th>
<th><a href="Glottal_consonant" title="Glottal consonant">Glottal</a></th>
<td rowspan="8" style="font-size:80%">1. Spelt <b>ng</b>, always <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/ŋ/</span>.<sup id="cite_ref-93" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-93"><span>[</span>93<span>]</span></a></sup><br />
<p>2. <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/t/</span> may be a glottal stop between vowels or word final.<sup id="cite_ref-Johnston.2C_Paul_1997_p.501_94-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Johnston.2C_Paul_1997_p.501-94"><span>[</span>94<span>]</span></a></sup> In Ulster dentalised pronunciations may also occur, also for <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/d/</span>.<br />
3. In Northern dialects the clusters <b>kn</b> and <b>gn</b> may be realised as <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/kn/</span>, <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/tn/</span> and <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/ɡn/</span><sup id="cite_ref-Johnston.2C_Paul_1997_p.501_94-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Johnston.2C_Paul_1997_p.501-94"><span>[</span>94<span>]</span></a></sup> e.g. <i>knap</i> (talk), <i>knee</i>, <i>knowe</i> (knoll), etc.<br />
4. The cluster <b>nch</b> is usually realised <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/nʃ/</span><sup id="cite_ref-95" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-95"><span>[</span>95<span>]</span></a></sup> e.g. <i>brainch</i> (branch), <i>dunch</i> (push), etc.<br />
5. Spelt <b>th</b>. In Mid Northern varieties an intervocallic <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/ð/</span> may be realised <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/d/</span>.<sup id="cite_ref-96" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-96"><span>[</span>96<span>]</span></a></sup> Initial 'th' in <i>thing</i>, <i>think</i> and <i>thank</i>, etc. may be <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/h/</span>.<sup id="cite_ref-Johnston.2C_Paul_1997_p.507_97-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Johnston.2C_Paul_1997_p.507-97"><span>[</span>97<span>]</span></a></sup><br />
6. Both <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/s/</span> and <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/z/</span> may be spelt <b>s</b> or <b>se</b>. <b>Z</b> is seldom used for <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/z/</span> but may may occur in some words as a substitute for the older &lt;<span lang="ang" xml:lang="ang">ȝ</span>&gt; (<a href="Yogh" title="Yogh">yogh</a>) realised <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/jɪ/</span> or <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/ŋ/</span>. For example: <i>brulzie</i> (broil), <i>gaberlunzie</i> (a beggar) and the names <i><a href="Menzies" title="Menzies">Menzies</a></i>, <i><a href="Finzean" title="Finzean">Finzean</a></i>, <i><a href="Culzean" title="Culzean" class="mw-redirect">Culzean</a></i>, <i><a href="Mackenzie_(surname)" title="Mackenzie (surname)">Mackenzie</a></i> etc.<br />
7. Spelt <b>ch</b>, also <b>gh</b>. Medial 'cht' may be <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/ð/</span> in Northern dialects. <i>loch</i> (fjord or lake), <i>nicht</i> (night), <i>dochter</i> (daughter), <i>dreich</i> (dreary), etc. Similar to the German "Na<b>ch</b>t".<sup id="cite_ref-Johnston.2C_Paul_1997_p.499_98-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Johnston.2C_Paul_1997_p.499-98"><span>[</span>98<span>]</span></a></sup> The spelling <b>ch</b> is realised <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/tʃ/</span> word initially or where it follows 'r' e.g. <i>airch</i> (arch), <i>mairch</i> (march), etc.<br />
8. Spelt <b>r</b> and pronounced in all positions,<sup id="cite_ref-99" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-99"><span>[</span>99<span>]</span></a></sup> i.e. <a href="Rhotic_consonant" title="Rhotic consonant">rhotically</a>.<br />
9. <b>W</b> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/w/</span> and <b>wh</b><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/ʍ/</span>, older <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/xʍ/</span>, do not merge.<sup id="cite_ref-Johnston.2C_Paul_1997_p.499_98-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Johnston.2C_Paul_1997_p.499-98"><span>[</span>98<span>]</span></a></sup> Northern dialects also have <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/f/</span> for <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/ʍ/</span>.<sup id="cite_ref-Johnston.2C_Paul_1997_p.507_97-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Johnston.2C_Paul_1997_p.507-97"><span>[</span>97<span>]</span></a></sup> The cluster <b>wr</b> may be realised <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/wr/</span>, more often <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/r/</span>, but may be <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/vr/</span> in Northern dialects<sup id="cite_ref-Johnston.2C_Paul_1997_p.507_97-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Johnston.2C_Paul_1997_p.507-97"><span>[</span>97<span>]</span></a></sup> e.g. <i>wrack</i> (wreck), <i>wrang</i> (wrong), <i>write</i>, <i>wrocht</i> (worked), etc.</p>
</td>
</tr>
